{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958032801/0209.xml":{"full_text":"r\nMMMM\nYour Union\nAnd Mine\n\n\nBy RICHARD T. GOSSER\nVice President, UAW\ni\nI\nONE OF the chief problems facing organized labor to\nday maybe the top one is the attempt by some\nemployers to destroy the Labor Union movement. Every\nwhere I go, all I hear is: \u201cWhat about the \u2018Right-to-Work\u2019\nBill\u201d which has now been given a fancier name, \u201cThe\nRight to a Free Choice\u201d Bill to confuse and fool people easier.\nI recognize how frantic the Chamber of Commerce, the\nManufacturers Association and other people in Ohio have be\ncome over this. We should recognize right out that the only pur\npose the people pushing this bill have is to destroy free trade\nunions. Unless we are on our guard and work hard to prevent\nthis we will find ourselves back to where we were in the Depres\nsion Days of the early Thirties.\nFor the next several weeks I intend to devote my column\ninto all phases of this problem, because it is one on which your\nstandard of living, your bread-and-butter depends. I want you\nto know why some employers are spending so much money to\nget this law passed so you will appreciate what all workers are\nup against and why it is important for you to get into this fight\nand defeat this Bill.\nFirst off, let\u2019s take this name \u201cRight to Work,\u201d which has\nbeen changed. This law has nothing to do with the real Right\nto Work. Right now our Community has 20.000 people unem\nployed.and who, believe me, want to have the right to work.\nMany of them, especially those unemployed with large families,\nare losing their cars, their furniture and other household goods,\nand going on short rations because this \u201cright to work\u201d just\ndoesn't exist for them.\ni\nI\nWHY DON\u2019T the Chamber of Commerce, the Manufacturers\nand other selfish employers give these people the right to work\ninstead of playing a hoax upon them and the rest of the people?\nI can assure them that our Labor Union and others in the Com\nmunity will gladly join hands with them if they will show us\nwhere these jobs are.\nGiving people the right to work is not the question involved.\nThe question is how can the Ohio Chamber of Commerce and\nthe Manufacturers Association fool the people into destroying\nthe Labor Movement. The first step in this campaign is to put a\nlabel on it like \u201cThe Right to Free Choice\u201d to mislead the public\nas to what actually is involved in this drive to change the law.\nThe Chamber of Commerce and the Manufacturers and\nother selfish employers are not bothering to tell the people that\nworkers had a free choice when they voted to organize a union\nin the plant or shop in which they are now working. Wherever\na labor union now exists, a free and democratic election was\nheld under the auspices o.f the United State Government or some\nother government body. By secret ballot the workers then voted\nfor a Union to represent them They did this because they knew\nthat collectively they could meet and bargain with the company\nfor better wages, better working conditions while individually\n1 they were helpless against the employer.\nThis is the condition which some employers want to go back\nto. They are hoping to fool enough people to make it possible.\nThe employers putting up the money for this campaign recog\nnize, if some of our members have forgotten, that Labor Unions\nhave put people ahead of profits and that there will be more\nprofits if the employers can get rid of Unions.\nI\nI\nEMPLOYERS KNOW and workers should realize it too,\nthat the Taft-Hartley Act has always been a bar to taking a\nworker's job away from him. If the Union was so inclined the\nmost it could do is expel a member and stop taking his dues.\nSpeaking of the International Union I represent which has over\n100,000 members in the State of Ohio, there have been but three\npeople expelled in the last seven years. In fact only a handful\nof workrs has been expelled since the existence of our Union.\nI state this to expose the hoax that people in our Unions didn't\nhave a \u201cfreedom of choice\u201d or that Unions took away workers'\njobs by letting them remain on the membership rolls.\nWe all should bear in mind\u2014and this is important and you\nwon\u2019t find the Chamber or Manufacturers mentioning it\u2014that\nin a free and democratic society, the majority rules and the\nminority abides by the decision. You won\u2019t find the employers\ni asking their non-union members whether they, too, want the\nraise and the pension and other better working conditions won\nfor them by their union brothers. The non-union members have\nno hesitation picking up the gains won by unions in their plant.\nAll they want is NOT to have to share the costs or the respon\nsibilities.\nWhen we talk about \u201cRight to Work\u201d or \u201cFreedom of\nChoice\u201d let's look back and recall what Labor Unions have won\nfor its members and the entire population in better living stand\nards. Let us ask ourselves whether what we have now could\nhave been gotten without Unions. I shall show in this way why\nsome employers are seeking to destroy Organized Labor.\n29 Delegates From Local 12\nTo Attend Ohio CIO Parley\nLocal 12 will send 29 delegates with a bloc represent\ning 189 votes to the Ohio CIO Convention which will act\non merger of the states labor organizations in Cleveland\nI beginning May 5, President Clem Holewinski announced.\nThe Ohio CIO Council will meet May 5 and two days\nlater it and the state Federa\ntion of Labor (AFL) are\nscheduled in joint session\nand adopt a constitution and\nelect officers.\nDelegates from Local 12 Units\nwill be distributed as follows:\nAcklin, 1 delegate, 4 votes;\nAuto-Lite, 3 delegates and 27\nvotes; Barrett, 1 and 4; Bing\nham, 1 and 3; Buddies, 1 and 2;\nChampion, 3 and 21; Continen\ntal, 1 and 6; DeVilbiss, 1 and\n7; J&L, 1 and 3.\nMather. 1 and 5; National\nSupply, 1 and 6; Toledo Pipe\nThreading, 1 and 2; Spicer, 2\nand 16; Spicer Office, 1 and 3;\nSurface Combustion, 1 and 2;\nTillotson, 1 and 2; Willys, 5 and\n148; Local 12 Unit Pool, 3 dele\ngates with 28 votes.\nNames of all delegates have\nto be in the office of President\nClem Holewinski by April 18 in\norder for credentials to be made\nout properly.\nCIO Calls Convention\nThe Call for the Special 19th\nConstitutional Convention of the\nOhio CIO Council was mailed to\nthose affiliated units that have\npaid\ntheir\nper\ncapita\nthrough\nJanuary. However, for delegates\nto be seated at the convention,\nper capita must be paid through\nFebruary.\nPurpose of the convention is\nto ratify the agreement for\nmerger with the Ohio State\nFederation of Labor and to ap\nprove the proposed Constitution.\n1\nThe First Constitutional Con-i\nvention of the new Ohio AFL\nI CIO will then be held May 7\nto 9 in Cleveland. I\nI\nSUB Appeal\nHearing Set\nFor April 1-2\\\nHearings on the supple-\nmental unemployment bene-\nfits case in Ohio will be held i\nApril 1-2 in the Seventh Dis\ntrict Court of Appeals at\nYoungstown.\nThe appeal on a Common\nPleas Court decision, which\nruled that SUB payments\ncould be made the same time\nas state jobless benefits, was\nasked by the Ohio Bureau of\nUnemployment Compensation)\nThe appeal was filed almost\nimmediately after Common\nPleas Court Judge Erskine\nMaiden signed a journal entry\non the case.\nJames Tichenor, BUC ad\nministrator, filed the appeal\nupon, orders from Governor\nC. William O\u2019Neill.\nA stay of execution, which\nwill hold up SUB payments,\naccompanied the appeal.\nI\nI\nTOLEDO UNION JOURNAL\nTHEONIY I ARiAsom MEMeDAT -el-.. .2\nTHE\nONLY\nt\n$3\nL ABIOIR\u00ae N E WS.P.A P E\n595 Sedettas\n\nAt\nl* 5\nig\n11\na\nsts\nWEE\n(Mti\n\n2:\nPU B LASIH ED EVER\n\nWEEK IN TOLEDO\n?2\u2018m\n1.9\n\n4 j\n*3t\nE\n**es\n444\n47%\nae\"\u2018982,29aP\ngecuceoueenecnontnyc*099*7**\nI\nI VOL. 16, NO. 13\nPMP227W..\nPublished By Organized Libor\n425 Winthrop St., Toledo, Ohio\n3\nTOLEDO, OHIO, FRIDAY, MARCH 28, 1958\nPAnvsK. PUs. M.\nI\nI\nI\nI\nI\nExplaining Union\u2019s Position\nLabor\u2019s position on the proposed Ohio Constitutional\nAmendment to bust Unions was explained to the West\nToledo Kiwanis Club at its meeting Tuesday. Left to\nright are Burt Whitehead, Jr., program chairman, UAW i\nVice-President Richard T. Gosser and Kiwanis President\nJohn W. Potter.\n\u2014Union Journal photo\nThis\nWeek\nin\nCity Couneil:\nCity\u2019s Revenues Fall\nOff; Recession Blamed\nThe continuing recession in Toledo is causing a decline\nin the City\u2019s revenues and could lead to a budget deficit\ndespite the economies proposed by the City Manager, a re\nport by the Finance Department indicated.\nAn operating revenue report for February submitted\nMonday to City C o u n c 11\nshowed that many of the\nfunds were not coming up to\nthe estimates made.\nI\nThe report showed a sharp\ndecline in city income tax col\nlections for the month which\nwere even below February, 1957\nwhen $901,046 was taken in. Col\nlections last month dropped to\n$787,540 which was $142,460 be\nlow the total estimated for Feb\nruary.\nTotal receipts for all funds,\nthe report showed, for February\ntotalled $1,475,804 compared to\nestimates of revenue of $1,666,\n158.\nWater Sales Decline\nShowing the affect of declin\ning business was income from\nseveral waterworks funds. Sale\nof water totaling $238,090 was\n$23,239 below what had been\nanticipated.\nAlso falling off was water\nmeter sales, new service such as\ntap-ins, and service repairs and\nservice charges. City officials\nBeemer Gets\nOK to Join\nComp Shop\nOrville Beemer, sub regional\ni director for Region 2-B, UAW,\nhas been granted a request to)\n.transfer, from the regional staff\nj to the Competitive Shop Depart\nment because of ill health.\nIn requesting the transfer, he\nsaid he had been in ill health for\nnearly a year and his condition\nwas being aggravated because of\nthe many details involved in his\npresent job.\nUAW Vice President Richard\nT. Gosser said that Mr. Beemer\nwould be assigned to organizing\nactivities for the International\nUnion in the West in the hope\nthat a change of scene and\nduties would help his recovery.\nHe will start on his new assign\nment Monday.\nMr. Beemer had 'been active!\nin the UAW for nearly 20 years\nand had been on the staff since\n1941. He was employed at Gor\ndon Bumper where he helped\norganize the plant and bring it\ninto Local 12. He served as\nchairman of the plant and was!\nprominent in Local 12 affairs. I\nLater he was appointed by Mr.\nGosser, then regional director,\nto the regional staff and assign\ned to organizing activities out\nof town. After World War II he\nwas assigned as an international\nrepresentative on the regional\nstaff to servicing plants in To\nledo and several years ago mov\ned up to an assistant to the reg\nional director.\nsaid the drop also was caused\nby a decline in new construction.\nOther barometers indicating\nthe fall-off in business were de\ni creased revenues from inspection\nof new buildings such as electri\ncal and plumbing, which were'\nnearly $2,900 less than expected\nand a decrease in revenue of $1,\n400 from parking meters.\nBus Revenues Drop\n1\nThe recession was also blamed,\nin part for a drop in revenue byi\nthe City Transit Commissioner!\nwho reported on the Communi\nty Traction Co.\u2019s operation for\nFebruary. I\nE. L. Graumlich noted that the\nIbus company suffered a net'\noperating loss of $20,838 last\nmonth. This compared to a loss\nof nearly $16,000 in January,\nand $9,457 in February, 1957.\nMr. Graumlich told Council,\nhowever, that while the bus\ncompany was not deriving its\nfull four per cent return al\nlowed, it was still making a prof\nlit and was much better off than I\n1 many traction companies in Ohio.\nI and elsewhere. I\nEarlier, Councilman Joseph\nl\nScalzo asked the bus company\nto come up with a study show\ning how it could give improved\nservice to areas that had been\nor would be annexed. He was\nassured such a study is being\nmade.\nYoungsters\nSnapping Up\nCamp Dates\nA year ago something pretty\nterrible NEARLY happened to\nLois Flynn, daughter of Mr. and\nMrs. D F. Flynn of 2544 Cen\nitennial Road.\nFor many months she had\nbeen looking forward to going to\nLocal 12 Summer Camp,\nsomehow her application never\nwas filed. It took a lot of run\nining around to get her into Sand\nLake. In fact last year she was\nBut\n*P* 3w9* 7*4\nthe very last camper accepted.\nThis year Lois decided things\nwere going to be different. First\noff. Lois talked so much about\ncamp that her sister, Kathleen,\n9, who is three years younger,\nwanted also to go to Local 12\nCamp.\nSecondly, the two talked\nso\nmuch about Uieir plans that\ntheir father decided that as soon\nas the applications were out he\nwas going to get them, fill them\nout and make sure Lois and\nKathy would not be overlooked.\nThat is how the two Flynn\ngirls got the honor of being the\nfirst to file their applications for\nSummer Camp.\nCamp Opening\nAlthough the\n_ opening of\nCamp is nearly three months\naway a lot of youngsters are\nhaving the same thoughts\nLois and Kathy.\nas\nI\ni Marian Spies, secretary of the\n'Summer Camp, reported that so\nfar 140 boys and ill girls have\nturned in applications for Sum\nmer Camp and more are con\nstantly arriving in each day's;\nmail.\nI\n1 The 251 applications received\nso far are the most turned in;\nthis early so a word to the\nwise is in order. If you are\nthinking of having your youngs\n\u2018ier go to camp, don't wait too\nlong. Applicants are accepted\non a \u201cfirst come, first served\u201d\n'basis so don't wait until the last\nminute. If you do you are liable\nto have a very disappointed\nI youngster on your hands, Local\n12 President Clem Holewinski\nwarned.\nPopular Weeks\nSo far the third and fourth\nweeks for boys, the periods July\n6 to 12 and July 13 to 19 are\ngetting a heavy play with 82\nasking for those periods.\nOf the 111 girls who have\nmade applications, 41 have re\nquested to go the first week,\nJuly 27 to Aug. 2, and 33 have\nasked for the second week,\nAug. 3 to 9.\nThe Women's Guild of Local\n12 Summer Camp is receiving\nmany requests from youngsters\nand organizations asking for the\nprivilege of going to Camp and\nits members hope to send as\nmany as possible in view of the\nsuccess of this year's St. Valen\ntine Dance. I\nAbout 10 shops have begun\nsending in applications in behalf\nof their members, all of which\nindicates that reservations will\nbe going pretty fast and it's later\nthan the calendar indicates.\n(Continued On Page 8)\nGetting Ready Early For Camp\n\u2014Union Journal photo\nKathy Flynn, 9, (left) and her sister, Lois, 12, apparently\nbelieve in the Scout motto, \u201cBe Prepared.\u201d\nWorst\nPostwar Recession\nGrips\nU.S.; Future Gloomy\n5.2 Million Jobless\nMake Quite a Few\nHow many is 5.2 million\nunemployed?\nAFL-CIO Pres. Georze\nMeany in his letter to the\nPresident put it this way:\n\u201cThere are twice as many\nunemployed workers as\nthere are inhabitants of\nthe entire city of Philadel\nphia, or for that matter,\nthere are as many unem\nployed as the total popula\ntion of the states of Wyom\ning, Vermont. Utah, South\nDakota, Rhode Island,\nNorth Dakota, New Mexico,\nNew Hampshire and Ne-\nvada.\u201d\nJoblessness\nAt 16-Year\nHigh Point\nUnemployment in mid-Febru\nary hit the highest level in 16\nyears and a top AFL-CIO eco\nnomist predicted that the peak\nis still to come.\nThe number of jobless in\ncreased 679,000 from January to\nreach a total of 5,173.000, up\nabout 2 million from February,.\n1957.\nIt was the highest total since\nAugust, 1941 when the number\nof jobless registered 5,500.000,\nor about 10 per cent of the labor\nforce.\nThe February, 1958 total con-1\nstituted 6. per cent of the total\ncivilian labor force. The labor\nforce percentage was 5.8 in Jan\nuary, 1958. Prior to the current\ni recession it ranged between 4\nand 4.5 per cent.\ni Stanley H. Ruttenberg, direc\ntor of the AFL-CIO Dept, of Re\nsearch, predicted that the Feb\nruary figure will not be the\npeak of unemployment and\nwarned the recession was the\nmost severe\n(since 1937-38.\neconomic decline\nThe unemployment figures re\nleased jointly by the Labor and\nCommerce departments showed;\nthat joblessness was running at a\nhigher rate from the 1954 down-i\nturn and at about the same level\nas the 1949 recession.\ni\nThe mounting unemployment\nresulted in a further drop in the\naverage work week for factory\nworkers to 38.5 hours, the low\nest for any February since\nWorld War II.\nAverage weekly earnings in\nto\nmanufacturing\ncontinued\nshrink also to $80.85, a slight\ndrop from the January average\nand $1.56 below the February\n1957 average\nOther highlights of the em\nployment-unemployment report:\nInsured unemployment per\nsons covered by unemployment\ncompensation was up 1.4 mil\nlion from February, 1957 to a\ntotal of 2.1 million.\nThe national rate of insured\nunemployment was 7.5 per cent\ncompared with 4.4 per cent a\nyear earlier.\nFactory employment dropped\n300,000 from mid-January to\nmid-February to 15.6 million.\nThe number of unemployed\n15 weeks or longer increased by\n300,000 to 1,150,000. This figure\nhad remained well under the\nmillion mark since the spring of\n1955.\nAbout 3 per cent of the em\nployed were working short shifts\nin February.\nCarey Demands Action\nThe latest statistics on unem\nployment and other economic\nindicators touched off a demand\nfor action by the Administration\nB.I\nand Congress from James\nCarey, president of the Electri\ncal, Radio and Machine Work\ners. He wired Pres. Eisenhower\nurging him to call on industry\nfurther\nfor a moratorium\non\nlayoffs, security in employment\nand income by instituting guar\nanteed annual wage plans, in\ncreased wages to catch up with\nproductivity gains and cooper\native studies on automation.\nMeanwhile the Federal Re\nserve Board announced the third\nreduction in the discount rate\nsince the recession began, drop\nping it from 2.75 to 2.25 per\ncent.\n\nThe worst recession since the end of World War II\ngripped the country this week as signs multiplied that the\neconomic outlook would get worse before any real recovery\nsets in.\nAll the major yardsticks of economic activity pointed\ndownward and firmly estab-1\nlished the 1957-58 recession\nas exceeding in intensity and\ndamage the setbacks suffered in\n1948-49 and 1953-54.\nSituation Summarized\n1\nThe Federal Reserve Board\nreported a 3 point drop in\nindustrial production in Febru\nary bringing the decline in the\ncurrent recession to 15 points or\n10.3 per cent more than the\ndrop in either of the previous\npostwar slumps.\nThe board summarized the\neconomic situation:\n\u201cRecession in economic ac\ntivity continued in February.\nIndustrial production, employ\nment incomes, and retail sales\nagain declined and unemploy\nment rose to a new postwar\nhigh.\u201d\n2\nThe Commerce Dept, re\nported a $2 billion drop in\npersonal income in February as\ncompared to January and a $3.3\nbillion decrease from a year ago.\nWages and salaries exceeded\nthe general drop, falling off $2 4\nbillion from the January rate\nand $6.8 billion from February\n1957.\n9 The Labor Dept, reported\nthat new claims for unem\nployment insurance, a rough\nmeasure of new layoffs, rose to\n447,614 in the first week of\nMarch a week that normally\nshows a decline in claims.\nIn the last week of February\nthe number of workers collect\ning jobless benefits rose to 3,\n358,308 compared to 1,756,070\na year ago.\nA The Commerce Dept, re\n4 ported that business plans to\nspend $5 billion, or 13 per cent,\nless for new plant and equip\nment in 1958 than last year. Ex\ncept for public utilities all ma\njor industries expect to reduce\ntheir outlays during the year.\nThe 13 per cent drop would be\nthe worst since 1949.\n5\nThe Federal Reserve Board,\nwith the aid of the Univ, of\nMichigan's Survey Research\nCenter, reported that consumers\nwere cdncerned about the gen\neral business outlook and viewed\ntheir financial positions and\nprospects less favorably than a\nyear ago.\nThe sampling o f consumer\nconsumer confidence showed\nfewer families planning to buy\ndurable goods and that prospects\nfor new car sales were the low\nest since 1951.\n6\nRail Retirement Board re\nported that the number of\njobless railroad workers doubled\nsince a year ago with 11 per cent\nunemployed in February and in\ncreasing in March.\nI\nJobless Benefits Running Out\nRobert C. Goodwin, director\nof the Labor Dept.'s Bureau of\nEmployment Security, told a\nHouse Labor subcommittee that\nthe number of persons exhaust\ning unemployment benefits is\nrising and can be expected to\nmove upward sharply in April\nand May.\nHe told the House group that\nthe rate at which unemployed\npersons are exhausting jobless\npay benefits has been rising\nsince December.\nThere was only one favor\nable indicator in the lot. The\nCommerce Dept, reported that\ncash dividend payments in\nFebruary were up $11 million I\nover January and that for the\nfirst two months of 1958 div\nidends were running at the\nsame rate as January and Feb\nruary 1957.\nWhile Congress and the Ad\nministration maneuvered on anti\nrecession programs the Federal\nReserve Board moved in on the\nmonetary front for the second\ntime in a month with a one-half\nper cent cut-in reserves required\nof member banks.\nCould Reduce Interest\nThe move is aimed at making\nmore money available for loan\npurposes and possible heavy\nTreasury financing. The larger\nreserves available to banks could\npossibly help in lowering inter\nest rates.\nThe continuing deepening of\nthe\nrecession\nbrought new\n=m\nLay-offs\nIncreasing\nIn Toledo\nSigns that the unemployment\nsituation in Toledo was grow\ning bleaker began to crop up as\nthe state and federal govern\nments continued their \u201cwait-and\nsee\" attitude.\nIncreases i n unemployment,\nmore temporary plant shutdowns\n'and rises in exhaustion of un\nemployment compensation bene\nfits contradicted a forecast by\nPresident Eisenhower that things\nwould get better in March.\nI\nAt Champion Spark Plug,\nwhere employment had been re\nlatively stable, the company an\nnounced that beginning Monday\n211 men and women would be\nlaid off. The reason given was\na change in production sche\ndules.\nThe layoffs will involve 85\nwomen whose seniority dates af\nter Dec. 8, 1944. and 126 men\nwith seniority after March 30,\n1953.\nThe last layoffs at Champion\noccurred nearly a year ago when\n57 women were laid off March\n29, 1957 and another 15 followed\non May 24.\nPlant Shutdown Reported\nTwo other Toledo companies\nannounced they would begin\nworking three weeks out of four\n\u2014Unitcast and Toledo Pipe\nThreading.\nSurface Combustion laid off\n15 employees a week ago after\nreducing their work staff by 20\nthe previous work. Another\nsmall reduction was reported at\nJ&L Steel Barrel, which pared\nthe work force of 275 by one\nthird.\nThe Toledo office of the Ohio\nBureau of Unemployment Com\npensation said their last survey\nshowed that employment in the\narea had dropped by 5,000 since\nJanuary.\nAt the same time more per\nsons each month were continu\ning to use up their .jobless bene\nfits. The rate for February was\n372, compared to 276 in Janu\nary and 232 in December.\nA spokesman said that unless\nemployment began picking up.\nMay would mark a rapid rise in\nthe number of benefit exhaus\ntions.\ncalls for government action\nfrom union leaders.\nThe United Steelworkers ex\necutive board adopted a resolu\ntion calling for action now \u201cnot\nnext month\u201d, adding that a \u201creal\ndepression\u201d exists in the steel in\ndustry. The board urged a nine\npoint program including tax\ncuts, raising jobless benefits and\nstandards, a public works and\nexpanded federal housing pro\ngram. school construction, aid\nfor distressed areas, increase in\nthe minimum wage and \u201cimple\nmentation\u201d of the Employment\nAct of 1946.\nKennedy Asks Excise Cut\nW. P. Kennedy, president of\nthe Brotherhood of Railway\nTrainmen, warned that legisla\ntive action is needed on the rail\nroad front and called for strong\n(Continued On Page 8)\n0000000000\nGosser To Address\nEducational League\nWhat are the chances for\njob opportunities and the\nbackground of the present re\ncession will be gone into by\nUAW Vice President Richard\nT. Gosser at the monthly Edu\ncational Meeting Friday\n(March 28) at 8 p.m. in Parlor\nA, Local 12 Hall, 425 Winthrop\nStreet.\nMr. Gosser will discuss To\nledo\u2019s status and future with\nan insight that is given to him\nby virtue of his service as a\nmember of the Port Authority\nCommission and the Toledo\nIndustrial Development Coun\ncil.\naa**a***a*******a***a*aaa***aa\nVVUUWVVUVVVVVVVVVVVVUUeeeew\nI\nPlease DO NOT Patronize Lasalle\u2019s","height":"26660","width":"19328"}}
